headline: CNN This Morning
subHeadline: Harry Dunn is Interviewed about Receiving Gold Medal; Ultra- processed Foods May Increase Dementia; Christmas Tree Prices Higher. Aired 6:30-7a ET

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Welcome back, everyone, to CNN THIS MORNING.Here is what's coming up. Republicans are slowly turning on Trump for his comments about the Constitution, but many still remain silent. Hours from now, congressional leaders will host a medal ceremony honoring the police who defended the Capitol. Officer Harry Dunn is going to join us live straight ahead. And a sweet surprise. Neil Diamond popping up in New York City with a rare, impromptu performance. That incredible moment and how fans reacted straight ahead.

utterances.speaker: POPPY HARLOW, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Can't wait to see that.Well, today, we will find out what Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell thinks about former President Trump calling to terminate the Constitution. McConnell says he'll address all of that this afternoon at the former president says he didn't say the thing that he definitely said. Saturday, Trump posted this about the 2020 election. Quote, a massive fraud of this type and magnitude allows for the termination of all rules, regulations and articles, even those found in the Constitution. Well, fast forward two days, now here is what former President Trump is saying. Quote, the fake news is actually trying to convince the American people that I said I wanted to terminate the Constitution. No, that actually is what he said and what he wrote, as you just saw. So, now more Republicans are slowly coming forward to put some space between themselves and Trump on this. Here are Senators John Kennedy and Mitt Romney. (BEGIN VIDEO CLIP) SEN. JOHN KENNEDY (R-LA): I disagree with the president. The Constitution can be amended. The Constitution can be interpreted. But the Constitution can't be suspended. SEN. MITT ROMNEY (R-UT): Well, as you know, the Republican Party has long been the party of the Constitution. And so when President Trump says he wants to suspend the Constitution, he goes from being MAGA to being rhino. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: KAITLAN COLLINS, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: It's not just those two. Senator John Thune told CNN the Constitution is, quote, the principle, the bedrock of our country. I could not disagree more.Senator John Cornyn said, I don't know why anybody would say something like that. Certainly not an ex-president. Senator Lisa Murkowski said, it's an affront to our republic. Senator Mike Rounds, quote, no one is above the Constitution. Some senators, though, some Republicans, are claiming they have not seen what Trump said, like GOP Senator Roger Marshall, who declined to condemn the comments and said he thinks the media should be focusing elsewhere. (BEGIN VIDEO CLIP) SEN. ROGER MARSHALL (R-KS): I don't know what President Trump said about the Constitution. I just don't think that's the issue. I don't think that's what you all should be talking about. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Senator Lindsey Graham and Senator Tim Scott declined to weigh in at all.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: U.S. Capitol Police Officer Harry Dunn joins me now.Harry, thank you for joining. How you doing? OFFICER HARRY DUNN, U.S. CAPITOL POLICE: Hey, what's up, Don? Good to talk to you, man. I'm doing all right. How about you?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: It's good to - it's good to see you again. I'm doing very well.Listen, I just want to know how you're feeling about today, because you've wait a long time. Look, you said you want answers. This is just an acknowledgement, a recognition of what you and other officers went through. So, how are you feeling about that?

utterances.speaker: DUNN
utterances.sentences: Yes. I just - I tweeted out last night about when I - when I started this speaking out about what we experienced on January 6th. It was all about accountability for everybody who had any part of the failures. Who was responsible for any part of the failures that day to be held accountable. But it's also about justice.Today, though, this honor that wasn't sought out, it -- the historical significance behind it, it just means so much. And I'm truly honored and humbled to receive this. I was looking over some of the list of -- the list over of some of the recipients of the Congressional Gold Medal. And, man, to be in some of those people's company is truly an honor. So, I'm thankful for that.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, listen, again, it's an honor, but does this go towards accountability, you think, or is this separate and apart?

utterances.speaker: DUNN
utterances.sentences: I think it's separate. If they would just give a medal and that would be the end of it, then that wouldn't be enough. I'd decline it. You know, no thank you, get to the bottom of what happened. But I think that's separate. And I think the Justice Department is doing that, as we saw in some of the - the outcomes, the convictions that were last week and that are continuing to happen. So, I think it's slow but it - that's -- that the justice is happening, and the accountability. So --

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: We're coming up on almost two years since this happened, since you - you know, your life was at risk fighting for democracy, right, and for the peaceful transfer of power. We're coming up on two years. Where are you now in the two years? Have you had any sort of resolution, or are you still feeling angst about it almost two years later?

utterances.speaker: DUNN
utterances.sentences: You know, now it's kind of like I'm just waiting and seeing. I never knew that an investigation, or, you know, this could take this long. However, I've never also seen an insurrection happen before. So, I don't have any, you know, baseline to gauge it off of, you know, as far as timewise.But, you know, things are happening. Even if it's slow, things are happening. And I'm glad that the Justice Department is working on it and hopefully getting it right. I do have my days where I'm, you know, a little down, a little upset, a little angry. I don't think that will -- those will ever go away because the memories of what happened that day will be forever ingrained in my, in my - my head, and - and in American history. But I - I deal with it. And I know how to deal with it a lot better than I did when it first happened. So --

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. Listen, as a law enforcement officer, you took an oath. The former president of the United States also took an oath to the Constitution and is now saying that the Constitution -- or has said that the Constitution should be suspended. What do you make of that?

utterances.speaker: DUNN
utterances.sentences: That's a wild dude, man. Like, he -- just when you think he can't get any more outrageous, he just goes and does and says those things. But I'm not giving him any attention. Today is all about dedication to duty and the oath, to my co-workers and myself, and the Metropolitan Police Department took and fulfilled on that day. So, I don't want to give any attention and credit to that guy.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. Actually said it should be terminated, not suspended, but now he's trying to walk it back.You and Officer Michael Fanone and others are going to receive that award today, and it is well-deserved. We're so proud of you and we thank you for appearing on CNN THIS MORNING. Thank you.

utterances.speaker: DUNN
utterances.sentences: Thanks a lot, Don. Good talking with you, man.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You as well.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Is it just the meat stuff or like my daughter's vegetarian, so I heat up veggie nuggets, things like that?

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: It can be that, too.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: It's - yes, because it's all of those additives and things. You have to really read the label and look. And it's really the processed meats, too.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What about your hash browns?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I - I -- I'm bad. I'm from the south. Kaitlan's from the south. They know. And we know you make something better is you just fry it, right?

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: Yes, of course.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: So -

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: We order McDonald's to the set more days that not.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: True.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Listen - but, I mean, this is very serious.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: How -- like, how much did it increase the risk of cognitive decline? Because this is a serious story.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: Right. And so we know about the link between ultra-processed foods and things like cardiovascular disease, obesity, cancers, but we haven't really looked that much at how it's associated with cognitive decline. And so researchers here took about 10,000 individuals in Brazil, who are average age of about 50, followed them for an average of eight years, gave them a food questionnaire and looked at their cognitive function. And they found, as you mentioned in the intro, that if their daily consumption of ultra-processed food, those calories that counted for over 20 percent of their intake, that it was associated with cognitive decline, global cognitive decline and also decline in their executive function, that's the part of the brain that's used to process information and make decisions.And as you mentioned, it doesn't take a lot to get to that 20 percent. That's about 400 calories in a 2,000-calorie diet. And so how might this be happening? We think that these ultra-processed foods may increase inflation, they might affect our microbiome, the gut bacteria, that there's a link there. They may end up damaging the vascular system. And - but it is important to point out, this was not a cause/effect study. This was an association. So there are limitations there.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh, boy.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: Yes. But, I'm sorry!

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I know.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: Be mindful. Mindful.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thank you. You just ruined -- I'm going to change my lunch now. Salad. I'm going to get a salad.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Are you really?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Look, honestly, it's terrible, but you only have one life, and so I'm going to --

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Live it.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Live it.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: Well, they did find that if you eat an overall healthy diet, Don, that that could negate some of the - some of this effect.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. I don't have an overall healthy diet though.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Nice try, though, Doc.

utterances.speaker: NARULA
utterances.sentences: I tried.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Doctor. Really appreciate it.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks, Doctor.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: The price of Christmas trees going up this holiday season. We're going to discuss. Plus -(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP) NEIL DIAMOND, MUSICIAN (Singing): Touching me, touching you. Sweet Carline. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: A surprise performance from Neil Diamond on the opening night of the new musical about his life, made theatergoers feel so, so good!

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: That reminds me of Jimmy Buffett making his -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Oh, yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: (INAUDIBLE).

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I always wonder -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Well, I mean, we're kind of celebrating, but the truth is, inflation has hit America's bank accounts this year a little bit hard and now it's threatening to put a damper on holiday cheer. The price of real Christmas trees has skyrocketed this year with a vast majority of tree growers expecting a wholesale price increase anywhere from 5 percent to 15 percent. And those costs are being passed down to who?

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: The consumer. To you guys.CNN's chief business correspondent Christine Romans and CNN's business reporter Nathaniel Meyersohn, both join us. Good morning. We hate to put a damper on Christmas, but what is happening? Why are these prices going up, Ms. Romans?

utterances.speaker: CHRISTINE ROMANS, CNN CHIEF BUSINESS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: Higher - higher fuel costs, higher fertilizers costs. I mean you look at -- Christmas only comes once a year. And this year, compared with last year, a lot of the input costs are higher for these - for these tree growers. So, the wholesale prices could be up about 15 percent this year.What goes in must comes out - come out at the pay - you know, when you pay for it. HARLOW: Even though inflation has been easing? I guess it's sort of baked in. We bought our tree this weekend. It's - it's perfect, but very - it was very expensive. We buy a real --

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Mine's been up before -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Because you buy fake ones.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Well, no, I do - I buy a real one but we - this year we scaled back because, you know, I have to get up early and I can't - I can't - I don't have the energy to put up the real tree anymore and go find it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: The lamest - and like - anyway, it's vacuum the needles.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: It was expensive this year.

utterances.speaker: NATHANIEL MEYERSOHN, CNN BUSINESS REPORTER
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, wholesale prices up 5 percent to 15 percent, being driven by higher labor costs, higher transportation costs. Most of the trees in this country grown in North Carolina, Oregon and Pennsylvania, and they have to be delivered across the country. So that's - that's why prices are up.There are a few ways that customers can save. Big-box stores like Walmart will often offer discounts on Christmas trees. They want to draw in shoppers. They use them as loss leaders, and then get them to spend on decorations and gifts.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: MEYERSOHN
utterances.sentences: Everything you need for the holidays. And maybe if you want to save -- buy a smaller tree this year, or consider switch to artificial trees. Artificial trees, the retailers bought them about a year ago.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: MEYERSOHN
utterances.sentences: They locked in those prices before inflation hit.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Well -

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: A big sale cyber week on artificial trees. Big sales.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I was so against it and now I'm for it. I - but I - I bought an artificial tree and it's easy. You just pop it in, boom, put the lights to the thing.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: I'm 100 percent against it. We can fight it out later, but -

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes, we'll talk about it.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I agree and I'm team real trees.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. COLLINS

utterances.speaker: MEYERSOHN
utterances.sentences: Right. So Kohl's -- some of the stores that you wouldn't expect are rolling out self-checkout. Kohl's, Bed Bath & Beyond, H&M, Uniqlo, Zara. Self-checkout is very controversial. Some people love it. They think that it moves more quickly than going through traditional cashiers. Other people get so frustrated by it. Think about all of the errors. And then you hear, unexpected item in the bagging area or please place item in the bag.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. I have - it happens to me every - I am team real tree with Kaitlan, OK?

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: And real cashier?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And also jobs because they -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And jobs.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: But the problem is, they can't find the workers for these jobs.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: So, they're investing - we heard the Fed chief last week say that they're - you're going to expect more investment in technology to do jobs that they can't retain people for.I was just at a Uniqlo and bought, you know, a bunch of sweatshirts for the boys. And I was so surprised. You just dump it all in the bin.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I was just going to say -

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: And then it just - you wave your phone and you walk out. I mean it was so easy.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You don't have to scan it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You just put it in the bag and just put the bag on the thing, boom, and it just does it. ROMANSthen you just press - I - it was so easy. I could have spent a lot more money. And I think that's what they wanted me to do.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thank you, guys.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Team real tree, team real people.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Go spend more money. It's good for the economy.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: Real tree, real people.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Christine.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Real tree, bad for the environment (ph).
